{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8f042fde-8bd2-4b24-887c-066a8faf4140","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is an application-level bug, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs (`CLRLoad` logs from `mscoree.dll`) only track **which .NET runtime version gets loaded** — they won't reveal anything about your null reference.\n\n**To diagnose your NullReferenceException, try these instead:**\n\n1. **Read the stack trace** — it tells you exactly which line dereferenced `null`.\n2. **Enable first-chance exceptions** in your debugger (`Debug > Windows > Exception Settings` in Visual Studio).\n3. **Collect a crash dump** — use `dotnet-dump collect` or `procdump`, then analyze with `dotnet-dump analyze`.\n4. **Add logging** around the crash site to identify which object is `null`.\n\nWould you like help with any of these approaches? For example, I can invoke the **dump-collect** skill to guide you through capturing a crash dump, or help you analyze a stack trace if you share it.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ade48b37-eff7-47ce-abe0-3ed6da4b7b4f","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, CLR activation logs are about runtime selection/loading — they help diagnose issues like the wrong runtime being loaded, not application-level bugs like NullReferenceException. A NullReferenceException after startup is an application code bug, not a CLR activation issue.\n\n\nI should explain to the user that CLR activation logs won't help diagnose a NullReferenceException, and suggest more appropriate diagnostic approaches instead.","outputTokens":525,"requestId":"1B83:31BA5F:CB0B03:E89BC0:6A02830D"},"id"